	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-otto bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 parent" id="comment-5096" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-5096" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0994d5e2e158a24ba8017c2525d78263?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://ottodestruct.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Otto</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2010/wordpress-3-0-and-custom-post-types/comment-page-1/#comment-5096">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2010-09-29T14:26:11+00:00">September 29, 2010 at 2:26 pm</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>There&#8217;s plenty of good reasons to use Custom Post Types. As long as you&#8217;re not using them as, basically, categories. Which a lot of people seem to want to do.</p>
<p>If you want to make something that shows up in the &#8220;blog&#8221;, then don&#8217;t use a custom type for it. Just use a normal Post.</p>
<p>If, on the other hand, you want to make a new type of thing, which maybe has its own area for it and won&#8217;t be part of the blog, then a custom type makes sense.</p>
</div>

